snippet.textDisplay: I have some suggestions for the first bandana before folding the mask put inside a large gallon ziplock back. First cut the  ziplock off then cut it down both sides so it makes one strip place it inside in the center the fold it like she did in the video. I used hair ties  but I found it wouldn't stay on my ears. On each side of the hair ties I attached a old shoelace on each side of the hairties then tied it to the back of my head above my ears. It stayed on and was a lot more comfortable

snippet.textDisplay:
Without a seal around the edges of the mask, this is essentially worthless as a filter for the air you breathe. As you inhale, the air around your face will take the path of least resistance toward the vacuum created by taking a breath. As it is easiest for air to flow in around your nose and not through the fabric, you are getting no benefit from this mask. This is a false sense of security.


In case you are wondering how I know this, having spent almost 20 years as a surgical assistant to an oral surgeon I got to spend some time in the hospital and when I first started I was upbraided by my doctor about not having my mask secured tightly against my face around my nose and under my safety glasses is it did nothing to prevent me from breathing aspirant from the surgical site as the drill cut soft tissue and bone.
